 |editor-last=Anderson |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2017\u20132018 |year=2017 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-1-4722-3397-4 |pages=254\u2013255}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mohamed Diam\u00e9}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160622091801/http://www.hullcitytigers.com/team/player-profile/mohamed-diame/17 Mohamed Diam\u00e9 profile] at the official [[Hull City A.F.C.]] website\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Al Ahli SC (Doha) squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Senegal squads\n| bg = green\n| fg = yellow\n| bordercolor = silver\n| list1 = \n{{Senegal squad 2012 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Senegal men's football squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Senegal squad 2017 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diame, Mohamed}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cr\u00e9teil]]\n[[Category:French people of Senegalese descent]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:French Muslims]]\n[[Category:Senegalese footballers]]\n[[Category:Senegal international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:RC Lens players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n[[Category:CD Linares players]]\n[[Category:Rayo Vallecano players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Wigan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Al Ahli SC (Doha) players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in Qatar]]\n[[Category:2012 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:2017 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:INF Clairefontaine players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French-Senegalese footballer}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Mohamed Diam\u00e9\n|image          = Mohamed Diam\u00e9 with West Ham United.jpg\n|image_size     = 200\n|caption        = Diam\u00e9 playing for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2012\n|fullname       = Mohamed Diam\u00e9<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1987|6|14|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman2010/11\">{{cite book |editor-first=Barry J. |editor-last=Hugman |title=The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311 |year=2010 |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-601-0 |page=117}}</ref>\n|birth_place    = [[Cr\u00e9teil]], France\n|height         = 1.84 m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/mo-diam\u00e9-224974/ |title=Mo Diam\u00e9 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref>\n|position       = [[Midfielder]]\n|currentclub    = [[Al Ahli SC (Doha)|Al-Ahli]]\n|clubnumber     = 21\n|youthyears1    = 2000\u20132003\n|youthclubs1    = [[INF Clairefontaine]]\n|youthyears2    = 2003\u20132005\n|youthclubs2    = [[RC Lens|Lens]]\n|years1         = 2005\u20132007\n|clubs1         = [[RC Lens|Lens B]]\n|caps1          = 28\n|goals1         = 1\n|years2         = 2007\u20132008\n|clubs2         = [[CD Linares|Linares]]\n|caps2          = 31\n|goals2         = 1\n|years3         = 2008\u20132009\n|clubs3         = [[Rayo Vallecano]]\n|caps3          = 35\n|goals3         = 1\n|years4         = 2009\u20132012\n|clubs4         = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n|caps4          = 96\n|goals4         = 5\n|years5         = 2012\u20132014\n|clubs5         = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]\n|caps5          = 71\n|goals5         = 7\n|years6         = 2014\u20132016\n|clubs6         = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n|caps6          = 50\n|goals6         = 13\n|years7         = 2016\u20132019\n|clubs7         = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n|caps7          = 97\n|goals7         = 5\n|years8         = 2019\u2013\n|clubs8         = [[Al Ahli SC (Doha)|Al-Ahli]]\n|caps8          = 10\n|goals8         = 0\n|nationalyears1 = 2012\n|nationalteam1  = [[Senegal national under-23 football team|Senegal Olympic]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 4\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 2011\u20132017\n|nationalteam2  = [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]]\n|nationalcaps2  = 31\n|nationalgoals2 = 1\n|club-update    = 15:14, 25 November 2019 (UTC)\n|ntupdate       = 08:19, 14 January 2018 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Mohamed Diam\u00e9''' (born 14 June 1987), also known as '''Momo Diam\u00e9''',<ref name=\"Momo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.afrikansoccer.com/2011/05/sevilla-track-senegal-midfielder-momo-diame/|title=Sevilla track Senegal midfielder Momo Diame|accessdate=21 May 2011|date=18 May 2011|publisher=Afrikan Soccer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606032345/http://www.afrikansoccer.com/2011/05/sevilla-track-senegal-midfielder-momo-diame/|archivedate=6 June 2011}}</ref> is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Al Ahli SC (Doha)|Al-Ahli]] as a [[midfielder]].\n\nThough born in France, Diam\u00e9 represented [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] at international level and made 31 appearances before retiring from national duty in 2017.\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nDiam\u00e9 was born in the Paris suburb of [[Cr\u00e9teil]] and he was selected to attend the [[INF Clairefontaine|Clairefontaine academy]] between 2000 and 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fff.fr/presentationfff/actualite/418646.shtml |title=INF, formateur de talents |accessdate=29 December 2012 |publisher=French Football Federationd |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114014916/http://www.fff.fr/presentationfff/actualite/418646.shtml |archivedate=14 November 2012 }}</ref> Diam\u00e9 began his professional career in 2003 with [[RC Lens]], but left four years later after facing health problems.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://descubrepromesas.blogspot.com/2008/09/mohamed-diame.html|title=Profile|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=21 September 2008|language=Spanish|publisher=descubrepromesas}}</ref> After a full recovery, he signed for lowly Spanish side [[CD Linares]] in 30 July 2007,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Garc\u00eda Ca\u00f1o|first1=Pablo|title=Diame convence a Braojos y se queda en el CD Linares|url=http://www.ideal.es/jaen/prensa/20070731/deportes_jaen/diame-convence-braojos-queda_20070731.html|website=Ideal|accessdate=3 August 2016|language=Spanish|date=31 July 2007}}</ref> and moved to [[Rayo Vallecano]] the following year,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Agencia EFE|authorlink1=Agencia EFE|title=Diam\u00e9 ficha por el Rayo Vallecano|url=http://www.lavozdigital.es/cadiz/20080621/deportes/mas-futbol/diame-ficha-rayo-vallecano-20080621.html|website=La Voz Digital|accessdate=3 August 2016|language=Spanish|date=21 January 2008}}</ref> helping the [[Madrid]]-based team to a [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|mid-table position]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], after being promoted in the [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2007\u201308 season]]. During his time with Rayo it was reported that [[La Liga]] giants [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] were interested in signing the midfielder,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/barcelona-real-madrid-battle-rayo-vallecano-star-mohamed-diame-217692|title=Barcelona, Real Madrid battle for Rayo Vallecano star Mohamed Diame|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=21 December 2008|publisher=Tribal Football}}</ref> as well as [[Premier League]] side [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.imscouting.com/global-news-article/the-lowdown-on-arsenal-target-mohamed-diame/1159/|title=The lowdown on Arsenal target Mohamed Diame|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=25 January 2009|publisher=IMScouting}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nOn 22 August 2009, Diam\u00e9 joined [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/8205476.stm|title=Wigan complete capture of Diame|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=22 August 2009|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> The transfer had earlier been temporarily put on hold, after alleged heart problems were found.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2009/08/14/futbol/equipos/rayo/1250232313.html|title=El coraz\u00f3n de Diam\u00e9 frena su fichaje por el Wigan|trans-title=Diam\u00e9's heart halts signing with Wigan|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=14 August 2009|author=Froil\u00e1n Mora|language=Spanish|newspaper=Marca|location=Madrid}}</ref> Diam\u00e9 made his debut the same day as his transfer, in a 5\u20130 defeat to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8209298.stm|title=Wigan 0\u20135 Man Utd|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=22 August 2009|author=Chris Bevan|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Wigan against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 6 February 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8493730.stm|title=Sunderland 1\u20131 Wigan|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=6 February 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> At the end of the 2011\u201312 season, he left Wigan after declining their offer to extend his contract.<ref name=Bosman>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Simon|title=Liverpool and Spurs lead chase for Diame with midfielder set to leave Wigan for free|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2144709/Mohamed-Diame-leave-Wigan-Athletic.html|accessdate=13 June 2012|newspaper=Daily Mail|location=London|date=15 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\nOn 20 June 2012, Diam\u00e9 joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20120620/diame-deal-agreed_2236884_2817081|title=Diame deal agreed|date=20 June 2012|publisher=West Ham United F.C.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622055808/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20120620/diame-deal-agreed_2236884_2817081|archivedate=22 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18521050|title=Mohamed Diame to join West Ham from Wigan on a three-year deal|date=20 June 2012|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Diam\u00e9 made his debut for West Ham on 18 August 2012 in a 1\u20130 win against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=West Ham 1\u20130 Aston Vila|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19221467|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> He scored his first goal for West Ham United in the 3\u20131 defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 6 October 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19768703|title=West Ham 1\u20133 Arsenal|date=6 October 2012|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> His second goal for the club was scored in the 3\u20131 victory over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 1 December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20474474|title=West Ham 3\u20131 Chelsea|date=1 December 2012|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 9 December 2012, Diam\u00e9 was injured in a match against Liverpool; it was initially thought he could be out for up to 3 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20661134|title=West Ham: Hamstring tear to sideline Mohamed Diame|date=9 December 2012|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In January 2013, after a number of clubs were reported to be interested in signing him, Diam\u00e9 stated that he wished to stay with West Ham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21182797|title=Mohamed Diame 'very happy' at West Ham despite Arsenal link|date=24 January 2013|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jan/24/tottenham-mohamed-diame-west-ham|title=Tottenham aim to tempt Mohamed Diam\u00e9 from West Ham for \u00a33.5m|date=24 January 2013|author=David Hytner|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref> Diam\u00e9 did not leave the club in the transfer window, and manager [[Sam Allardyce]] stated that it was an important decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21299380|title=West Ham: It was vital Mohamed Diame stayed \u2013 Sam Allardyce|date=1 February 2013|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Hull City===\n[[File:Mohamed Diame Hull City 2014.jpg|thumb|200px|Diame playing for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in 2014 against Everton]]\nOn 1 September 2014, Diam\u00e9 joined [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hullcitytigers.com/news/article/1415-diame-signing-1891684.aspx|title=Tigers Sign Mohamed Diame From West Ham|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=1 September 2014|publisher=Hull City A.F.C.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903142317/http://www.hullcitytigers.com/news/article/1415-diame-signing-1891684.aspx|archivedate=3 September 2014}}</ref> Two weeks later, he made his debut at the [[KC Stadium]], scoring against his former club West Ham in a 2\u20132 draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hull City 2\u20132 West Ham United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29105375|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 September 2014|date=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May 2016, Diam\u00e9 scored in the [[2016 Football League Championship play-off Final|Championship play-off final]] in a 1\u20130 win against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], giving Hull an immediate return to the [[Premier League]] after their relegation in the [[2014\u201315 Premier League|2014\u201315 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36348885|title=Hull City 1\u20130 Sheffield Wednesday|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 May 2016|date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\nOn 3 August 2016, Diam\u00e9 joined [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/aug/03/newcastle-sign-mohame-diame-hull-city|title=Newcastle sign Mohamed Diam\u00e9 from Hull City on a three-year contract|work=The Guardian|date=3 August 2016}}</ref> Diam\u00e9 scored his first goals for Newcastle when he scored twice in an [[EFL Cup]] win against [[Preston North End]] on 25 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37686639|title=Newcastle 6\u20130 Preston North End|publisher=BBC|date=25 October 2016 |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017 he had a training ground fight with teammate [[Jamaal Lascelles]]. The two players later apologised and offered to take the entire first team squad and staff out for lunch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/10/13/newcastle-pair-say-sorry-training-ground-fight-offer-whole-squad/|title=Newcastle pair say sorry for training-ground fight and offer whole squad a free lunch|date=13 October 2017|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=6 April 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHe was released by Newcastle upon the expiry of his contract at the end of the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/magpies-confirm-departing-players|title=Magpies confirm departing players|website=Newcastle United Football Club|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Al Ahli SC===\nOn 11 July 2019, Diam\u00e9 joined Qatari side [[Al Ahli SC (Doha)|Al-Ahli]] on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mohamed Diam\u00e9 au Qatar|url=https://www.francefootball.fr/news/Mohamed-diame-au-qatar/1039115|website=France Football|accessdate=16 July 2019|language=French|date=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 22 March 2011, Diam\u00e9 was called up to play for [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]], for whom he qualifies as his father was born in [[Dakar]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wiganlatics.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10429~2322156,00.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805212637/http://www.wiganlatics.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10429~2322156,00.html|url-status=dead|archivedate=5 August 2012|title=International Rescue!|accessdate=22 March 2011|date=22 March 2011|publisher=Wigan Athletic F.C.}}</ref> Diam\u00e9 made his international debut later that month.<ref name=NFT>{{NFT player|pid=42803|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Diam\u00e9 was announced as one of three over-age players in Senegal's squad for the 2012 Olympics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18754732|title=Senegal leave Papiss Cisse out of Olympic squad|date=7 June 2012|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He scored his first international goal for Senegal on 26 March 2016 in a 2\u20130 win against Niger in a [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] match.<ref name = \"Goal\">{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/03/26/africa/africa-cup-of-nations-qualification/senegal/niger/2038151 |title=Senegal vs. Niger  2\u20130|work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe retired from international football in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39256494|title=Mohamed Diame moves aside for new Senegal stars|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=13 March 2017|author=Oluwashina Okeleji|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDiam\u00e9 is Muslim.<ref>{{cite news|last=Din|first=Tusdiq|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/fasting-and-football-how-do-topflight-muslims-cope-2342187.html|title=Fasting and football. How do top-flight Muslims cope? |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=23 August 2011|accessdate=10 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n[[File:Mohamed Diam\u00e9.jpg|thumb|200px|Diame playing for [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in 2010.]]\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|18 May 2019}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup\n!colspan=2|League Cup\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[RC Lens|Lens B]]\n|2005\u201306<ref name=NFT/>\n|[[Championnat de France Amateur|CFA]]\n|28||1||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||28||1\n|-\n|2006\u201307<ref name=NFT/>\n|CFA\n|0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!28!!1!!colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014!!28!!1\n|-\n|[[CD Linares|Linares]]\n|[[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2007\u201308]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/j9406.html?temp=2007-08 |title=Diam\u00e9: Mohamed Diam\u00e9: 2007\u201308 |publisher=BDFutbol |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|31||1||1||1||colspan=2|\u2014||1<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearance in [[2008 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs]]</ref>||0||33||2\n|-\n|[[Rayo Vallecano]]\n|[[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2008\u201309]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/j9406.html?temp=2008-09 |title=Diam\u00e9: Mohamed Diam\u00e9: 2008\u201309 |publisher=BDFutbol |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|35||1||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||37||1\n|-\n|